This thread is for the discussion of scale plastic (and resin, PE, wood, etc) models kit
-Post photos of your builds in progress and your finished builds
-Have your builds critiqued or critique others
-Discuss tips and techniques
-Ask for advice or give advice to others

Always remember:
>No manufacturer is purely perfect or awful. ALWAYS research your kits before buying.

com:
Loli raccoon figma never

Toyline general info:
>http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Figma

Max Factory figma list & blog
>http://www.figma.jp/en/figma
>http://ameblo.jp/figma/
>http://www.goodsmile.info/en/products/category/figma

Reviews and news about GSC/MF products by Kahotan
>http://mikatan.goodsmile.info/en/
>http://ameblo.jp/gsc-mikatan/

Where to buy
>GSC Online Shop - some figmas only are available through their online shop
>Amiami - usual place for buying, to some people, shipping is a bit higher due to packaging
>Hobby Link Japan shipping is usual lower, but their prices are a bit higher, private warehaouse is available
>Hobby Search Japan - items stay in stock the longest
>Mandarake - search figma or フィグマ
>eBay/Amazon - only if you hate having too much money. Avoid bootlegs, you can spot them as 'Chinese version'
>http://jungle-scs.co.jp/ - Seems like you can fine some good deals here
>Check the BST threads, My Figure Collection for any offer/deal

Here's a link to the buyfag guide list of shops:
http://www.buyfags.moe/Full_guide#List_of_shops
If you're getting into the hobby, there's plenty of other useful information to find on the wiki.

In case someone is interested in the printable backdrops/dioramas & other papercraft stuff that Max Factory have in the download section of their site:
>http://www.maxfactory.jp/ja/mxf-downloads
here is a back up, Enjoy!
>https://www.mediafire.com/?7l9ar0z58cx43sa

Short illustrated posing guide by Max Factory
>http://ameblo.jp/figma/entry-11564427757.html (in moonrunes)
The S shape is always good advice though. The basic idea is that straight lines tend to look stiff.

Problems when swapping parts/accessories with your figmas? Check this advice
>http://www.goodsmile.info/en/post/3325

Tomytec's 1 inch scale section (1/12 stuff, little armory, vehicles and others)
>http://www.tomytec.co.jp/1inch/

name: Anonymous
com: Be honest, do you think this quality of figure is worth 25 dollars?
last_replies:
[{'no': 10183528, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)22:59:45', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'LOL', 'time': 1670903985, 'resto': 10181330}, {'no': 10183547, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)23:17:50', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'I wrote a really long post and thought better of it. Its all in the amortisation schedule of the tools. The problem with IP stuff (vs. army men or whatever) is you can't sell them on as easily and the nostalgia window is closing (or even worse, your licensing is time limited) vs. the durability of modern moulds. If only you were making sporks or pen parts, you could aim to pay them off over 50 years not 5 or 10.

It has little do with what is in the box itself, the box is usually more expensive than the contents but for the above. The cost of plastic is absolutely nominal.', 'time': 1670905070, 'resto': 10181330}, {'no': 10183567, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)23:30:49', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'It seems like in interviews the cost of materials is the first thing the corpos use as an excuse but here I am hearing plastic is basically worthless and it doesn't matter how much plastic a figure has, only pieces,', 'time': 1670905849, 'resto': 10181330}, {'no': 10183731, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)02:14:19', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10183567
The cost of plastic is going up like everything else, but not nearly as much as the cost of labor overseas. The easiest thing for manufacturers to tell to the normal public who doesn't know jack shit about production is to say the cost of 'materials' or cost of 'plastic' is going up. Technically 'materials' involves the steel used for tooling and all that too, so they aren't entirely lying.

What else are they gonna say? "The factories where poor Chinese women are spending 18hrs a day making our product are just now finally earning more humane wages, and also the cost of plastic per pound went up by 3 cents so your action figure will now cost $25 instead of $22." LOL they don't want to open that human rights/living wage can of worms for the public to pick apart.', 'time': 1670915659, 'resto': 10181330}, {'no': 10183860, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)06:15:55', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10183567
cost of materials do matter, but have you ever noticed who is the one that talks about it? Hasbro. Mattel. Bandai. Wall Street.
Because they're beholden to stockholders and always have the expectation that revenue/profits will outdo the last year/quarter, they exaggerate the effect.

These companies are raking in billions of dollars a year, in profit, yet they can't ever make as much money as last year, muchless less than last year. But you hsould know this story about publically traded companies by now.
In addition, the higher the position in sales a company is, the more pressure theyre under. So a company like Hasbro has to over-correct, faster and wider, than a company like Jazwares.

Hence Hasbro being the only major company right now selling children toys for $25.

And this isn't to say that Hasbro is wrong to charge as much as they do, because that's nothing but hippie poorfag nonsenses. Hasbro is a business and businesses exist to make money. This means that every company in the market will eventually reach the same price as Hasbro. How soon? Depends on the market, economy, and a variety of other factors.
No doubt, Hasbro hit the $25 (from $23) price point because of shipping costs going up 500%.
Other toy companies remain pre-plague prices despite that, likely hoping that that shipping cost would go down eventually.
Did it? Yes, but prices are still elevated and delays are a costly bitch. So even a company like McFarlane will have to raise prices as well. No doubt, there are various contracts in place made pre-plague that have helped them from overpaying too quickly (shipping, handling, manufacturing, etc), but those will run out and a new price will be negotiated, if it hasn't already.

Also, retailers can also dictate prices too. No doubt, Walmart and Amazon are taking note of how well $25 MLs are selling and seeing how that compares to sales from the past 5 years.', 'time': 1670930155, 'resto': 10181330}]

com:
Toys are returning from whence they came, from double jointed, more poseable figures to single jointed stiff lumps of plastic to save on costs with far more limited posing potential. Now this figure can't even stand up in this pose.

And yes the knees still look ugly even single jointed.

Do you see articulation going backwards in response to consumer price sensitivity?

sub: You have the key and cupboard from the novel/film The Indian in the Cupboard
com:
After placing a toy, model, figure, or sculpture of any kind into the cupboard and closing the door, you insert the key into the lock and twist. When you open the door once again, your inanimate object will be alive!

The rules are:
>The toy(s) must reasonably fit within pic related
>The toy(s) you animate will remain at their toy size - converted to living flesh, clothing, or whatever material the original character was made out of
>The toy(s) will be completely sentient and alive, with their own thoughts and emotions (Unless it is a toy of a non-sentient object like a weapon, vehicle, or prop)
>They will retain their canon personality and abilities, along with any memories they have of their non-toy lives up to that point - including relationships and enemies
>Whatever accessories they had on them will be recreated at that scale as well (Plastic turns into wood, steel, fictional material, etc.)
>If they are not from a work of fiction, they will assume they are a real individual from whatever era the toy represents (i.e. Little Bear, an Iroquois Chief, and Tommy Atkins, a WWII English army medic, from the book and movie)
>Construction/creative materials such as Play-Doh, Lego, or Meccano will become whatever the creator meant them to be when constructing them
>Blank slate/custom toy characters (Lego minifigures, custom-painted miniatures, wooden mannequins) will become whatever the creator imagined for them

Whenever you choose to reverse the process, they become a toy again and their consciousness returns to wherever it belongs.

One, I'm not the guy who said it was a new theater of war. Don't go assuming that it can be only one other person discussing the topic.
Two, it's pretty clear what the original poster meant was that Diaclone hasn't done anything specifically for naval or underwater combat. Yeah, they have animation of the standard land mechs and vehicles operating underwater, but that's cheap, boring, and doesn't mean anything for the actual toys themselves. I can take a toy tank and put it in the bath tub, doesn't mean it suddenly has the appeal of an actual submarine. The point is getting cool figures that are obviously designed for water combat, with torpedoes and harpoons and stuff. What >>10177460 did was go "um, ackshually" to point out a technicality that completely misses the point.
No one cares if the associated fiction has a few seconds of animation of the mechs underwater (not even fighting, mind you, so if you want to get technical you can't really say it's been explored as a theater of war, because there was no "war" going on there). The fiction is merely a secondary bonus to go along with the toys. This is a thread about toys, on a board about toys. People care about what the toys look like and do, not about if some random writer says "sure, these things totally work underwater too".', 'time': 1670857257, 'resto': 10145128}, {'no': 10183013, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)16:00:22', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10181341

com: New photo from their page, preorders soon?
last_replies:
[{'no': 10182866, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)13:21:01', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10181834
That's some expensive card!', 'time': 1670869261, 'resto': 10110074}, {'no': 10182892, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)13:42:20', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10182508
This is how many lines have been handling orders lately. In the past, this was for retailers to order solid cases of specific characters to bump up stock for online sales, but now stores are stocking shelves with these solid cases too. Look at Target stocking solid cases of a single Legends figure, or a single Jakks Sonic or Mario figure.

Theoretically, this should help prevent walls of single undesirable figures at a store, but now we're at the mercy of whatever toy manager or whoever places the orders not to be a fucking moron and order three solid cases of green Megaman. And I fully believe there will be many stores who get walls of a single figure just like we've seen plague Marvel Legends, Sonic, and Mario.

The one plus side to this is that the manufacturer can see which characters get re-ordered the most and can use that info to make better character selections for future waves down the line. So there's that at least, but I doubt anything will stop Jada from making dozens of Mega Man re-colors since that saves tooling dollars.', 'time': 1670870540, 'resto': 10110074}, {'no': 10182893, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)13:43:43', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10182866
Packaging IS expensive in the grand scheme of things. Paper card, plastic bubble, plastic trays, dies for making the bubble and trays, extra volume of larger packages taking up more space resulting in higher shipping costs, etc.', 'time': 1670870623, 'resto': 10110074}, {'no': 10182926, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)14:10:57', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10182893
I kinda struggle to see a simple change in packaging size accounting for literally a fifth of the item cost. For one thing, I don't think we'd be seeing so much toy packaging on retail shelves that dwarfs the item within - retailers clearly feel it's financially justified to ship a volumetric crapton of extra air in service of shelf presence.', 'time': 1670872257, 'resto': 10110074}, {'no': 10182990, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)15:22:54', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>10182926
There's dozens of factors. Shelf real estate is also a factor too. The more shelf your line has, the less shelf the retailer has to offer competing product alongside your items. So in that regard, a larger package may be beneifical if it outweighs the additional costs. But the most important factor was probably perceived value of the figure. If the package looks so massive with so much empty space that the consumer will feel like they got ripped off, then it's 100% better to go with a smaller package that gets filled out more.

Most likely thing I believe is that Jada realized how much the cost would be to produce the Mega Man figures and the cost came in below what they expected so they had more wiggle room to lower the MSRP. Like I said earlier, there is a LOT of tooling shared between Megaman figures. Lots of Robot Masters can use the same feet/thighs/hips/abdomen/arms too. That reduces production costs a ton compared to a line like Street Fighter with much larger figures and more unique parts.', 'time': 1670876574, 'resto': 10110074}]

name: Morphine-Kun
com:
Welcome back everyone, hope you're all doing well.

The time has come for us to finally have new releases in the line! By now most of everyone who ordered Olivier and Vania should have them in hand. Its seems the delay was worth it as Olivier seems to be one of the better releases in the line. Vania also seems to be a generally good release as people are having fun messing with her and Olivier. As of now, we only have one other figure up for Pre-Order right now, that being Bikini Clover. Currently we know that the Polynian and Touhou series will continue since Marisa is supposedly the next in line to go up. The official Poly 4Koma is still going and it seems its been well received as it gives little look into the everyday lives of the Polys we know. We also had a wonderful surprise in the form of the new Polynian MLL body! We finally have a counterpart to the Iana body. Aside from that things have been pretty quiet for the time being.

As always, here is the assistance e-mail for those who need it, so if any problem should arise, feel free to contact them over at "user_support@mile-stone.jp" or the shop you purchased the figure from.

Once again, feel free to share your photos and adventures, they add life and some fun to the thread. Also, welcome newcomers, we hope you enjoy your stay.

OP here.

I sculpt and since I use soft Chavant some seperate parts fall apart with the slightest movement.

So I was thinking about using some pins however stabbing yourself or cutting your finger on a wire pin is not fun.

So I was thinking about toy parts and lego since the pins must be hard and durable and not shatter into a 1000 peaces to ruin my clay (3D printed parts).

So the best option is for these pins to be smooth and have nothing the clay can grab on (that small technique peace that is a cylinder with holes in it is problematic since it will forever take clay into itself) So i need something smooth to not grab clay and that I can clean to not lose clay.

Also these pins have benefits since I intend to 3D scan my best works and and dissembling the model using a pin system is a great idea for a quick parts scan.

The color is because black is extra hard to 3D scan and red also now creates problems. This is also why I say no to shiny or transparent pins since they can confuse the 3D scanner.

Any suggestions of what I can use ?
These parts will forever be with my clay tools so I'm not afraid to keep them this way made dirty with clay.

Is there a good lego system for mounting these ins and expect them to hold some mass ?

PS: if you did not know I expect to cut away the pins in software.

Video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4bLPMMKv3mA

PS2: Feel free to give other suggestions of toy parts or anything else.

Previous Thread >>10161933

Toyline general info:
>http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Figma

Max Factory figma list & blog
>http://www.figma.jp/en/figma
>http://ameblo.jp/figma/
>http://www.goodsmile.info/en/products/category/figma

Reviews and news about GSC/MF products by Kahotan
>http://mikatan.goodsmile.info/en/
>http://ameblo.jp/gsc-mikatan/

Where to buy
>GSC Online Shop - some figmas only are available through their online shop
>Amiami - usual place for buying, to some people, shipping is a bit higher due to packaging
>Hobby Link Japan shipping is usual lower, but their prices are a bit higher, private warehaouse is available
>Hobby Search Japan - items stay in stock the longest
>Mandarake - search figma or フィグマ
>eBay/Amazon - only if you hate having too much money. Avoid bootlegs, you can spot them as 'Chinese version'
>http://jungle-scs.co.jp/ - Seems like you can fine some good deals here
>Check the BST threads, My Figure Collection for any offer/deal

Here's a link to the buyfag guide list of shops:
http://www.buyfags.moe/Full_guide#List_of_shops
If you're getting into the hobby, there's plenty of other useful information to find on the wiki.

In case someone is interested in the printable backdrops/dioramas & other papercraft stuff that Max Factory have in the download section of their site:
>http://www.maxfactory.jp/ja/mxf-downloads
here is a back up, Enjoy!
>https://www.mediafire.com/?7l9ar0z58cx43sa

Short illustrated posing guide by Max Factory
>http://ameblo.jp/figma/entry-11564427757.html (in moonrunes)
The S shape is always good advice though. The basic idea is that straight lines tend to look stiff.

Problems when swapping parts/accessories with your figmas? Check this advice
>http://www.goodsmile.info/en/post/3325

Tomytec's 1 inch scale section (1/12 stuff, little armory, vehicles and others)
>http://www.tomytec.co.jp/1inch/

com:
Babes and Monsters/Robots

Anyone else like that? And not in like a pervy way? Like you just buy women figs and all your male toys are giant robots or monsters or something similar?

I think I've always been like this. I've never really gravitated to human males as toys. I was luckily born in the 80s, so I had a lot of awesome monsters and robots to pick from in the 80s and 90s.

I started buying marvel legends and heman figs and noticed im still doing this. I have like 20 or 30 legends figs. Mostly women with a few big monster bafs. My male figs are like the Thing and retro Doom. My heman relvelations figs are all the girls and monster dudes.

I kind of blame the tail end of transformers and TMNT for this. They made a lot of monster bots around season 3 of transformers. And TMNT was like 3 April figs and 3000 different mutant dudes.

My sister was also into she ra, and I'd have the monster guys
